(728, 39, 'ncremental Approach\n\n*   The system is reengineered gradually, one step closer to the target system at a time.\n*   **Benefits:**\n    *   Easy detection of mistakes due to identifiable new components.\n    *   Easier for the client to detect progress through intermediate versions.\n    *   Less risky than the \"Big Bang\" method.\n*   **Disadvantages:**\n    *   Takes longer to complete due to multiple interim versions and careful version control.\n    *   The entire architecture of the system cannot be changed even if needed.\n\n##### 4.10.3 Partial Approach\n\n*   Only a part of the system is reengineered and then integrated with the non-engineered portion.\n*   **Steps:**\n    1.  Partition the existing system into two parts: one to be reengineered, the other not.\n    2.  Use either the \"Big Bang\" or \"Incremental\" approach to reengineer the chosen part.\n    3.  Combine the reengineered part and the non-reengineered part to form the new system.\n\n##### 4.10.4 Iterative Approach', '[0.043496974,-0.038350902,-0.020103235,0.0025812034,-0.009001991,0.012351396,0.091467254,0.02745282,-0.03165756,-0.01703329,-0.027701255,0.031100951,0.005504487,0.0064249043,0.029011693,0.021635305,0.04544255,0.04087561,-0.05567155,0.0013787289,0.012573341,-0.013129436,-0.03313196,-0.046391387,-0.0048199166,0.0017811274,0.026469257,-0.033206724,0.0039480994,0.021886818,0.023405468,-0.001618345,0.028615328,-0.06507085,0.03063286,0.07626102,-0.0052618547,-0.0103464285,0.017975124,0.037182756,-0.040029135,0.002019936,-0.03897024,0.0062759384,-0.010469701,0.004884108,-0.007851171,0.041787487,-0.037773427,0.015327479,-0.014605357,-0.014455684,-0.029332357,0.035627205,-0.013077544,-0.04614197,-0.034577273,0.031034403,0.018025499,-0.0008538003,0.020906707,-0.034429073,-0.02330826,-0.05474871,0.023839498,0.000634264,-0.034237545,-0.048176713,-0.08025599,-0.004857549,-0.009942207,0.07760875,-0.058998648,0.044004258,-0.0016083803,-0.036922608,-0.001418813,-0.05684336,-0.047334