(39, 2, NULL, 'Chapter 4.pptx.pdf', 'pdf', '## BMSE3014 Software Maintenance\n\n---\n\n### CHAPTER 4: RE-ENGINEERING\n\n#### 4.1 Introduction to Re-Engineering\n\n*   **Definition:** Re-engineering is the examination, analysis, and restructuring of an existing software system to reconstitute it in a new form and the subsequent implementation of the new form.\n\n*   **Goals of Re-engineering:**\n    *   Understand existing software system artifacts (specification, design, implementation, and documentation).\n    *   Improve the functionality and quality attributes of the system (e.g., evolvability, performance, reusability).\n\n#### 4.2 Risks Involved in Re-Engineering\n\n*   The target system may not have the same functionality as the existing system.\n*   The target system may be of lower quality than the original system.\n*   The benefits may not be realized in the required time frame.\n\n#### 4.3 General Objectives of Software Re-engineering\n\nSoftware systems are reengineered by keeping one or more of the following general objectives in mind:\n\n*   Improving maintainability\n*   Migrating to a new technology\n*   Improving quality\n*   Preparing for functional enhancement\n\n#### 4.4 Principles of Abstraction and Refinement\n\n##### 4.4.1 Principle of Abstraction\n\n*   The level of abstraction of a system\'s representation can be gradually increased by successively replacing details with abstract information.\n*   Abstraction allows for a view that focuses on selected system characteristics by hiding information about others.\n\n##### 4.4.2 Principle of Refinement\n\n*   The level of abstraction of a system\'s representation is gradually decreased by successively replacing aspects with more details.\n\n##### 4.4.3 Conceptual Levels of Abstraction\n\n*   **Conceptual Level:**\n    *   Describes the software in terms of very high-level concepts and its reason for existence (\"why?\").\n    *   Addresses the \"why\" aspects of the system.\n\n*   **Requirements Level:**\n    *   Describes high-level functional characteristics (\"what?\") of the system, leaving out details.\n    *   Addresses the \"what\" aspects of the system.\n\n*   **Design Level:**\n    *   Describes system characteristics (\"what and how?\") in detail, including major components, architectural style, interfaces, algorithms, and major data structures.\n    *   Addresses \"what\" and \"how\" aspects by answering questions about system characteristics and how they deliver functionalities.\n\n*   **Implementation Level:**\n    *   Describes the system at a very low level in terms of implementation details in a high-level language.\n    *   Addresses \"how\" exactly the system is implemented.\n\n##### 4.4.4 Re-engineering Processes: Abstraction and Refinement\n\n*   **Refinement Process:** `why? → what? → what and how? → how?`\n*   **Abstraction Process:** `how? → what and how? → what? → why?`\n\n#### 4.5 Principle of Alteration\n\n*   **Definition:** Alteration is the making of changes to a system representation without changing the degree of abstraction and without modification, deletion, or addition of information.\n\n#### 4.6 Models of Software Re-Engineering\n\n##### 4.6.1 General Model\n\n*(No specific details provided in the source content for the \"General Model\")*\n\n##### 4.6.2 Horse Shoe Model\n\n*   **Description:** The reengineering process is often divided into three stages:\n    1.  **Reverse Engineering:** May be required if the technological platform is obsolete or original creators are unavailable.\n    2.  **Software Reorganization (Software Restructuring):** Aims to improve key components of the system.\n    3.  **Forward Engineering:** Designing a new running system based on the restructured model.\n\n*   **Formula:** Reengineering = Reverse engineering + Δ + Forward engineering\n    *   \"Δ\" captures alterations made to the original system.\n    *   Two major dimensions of alteration are:\n        *   Change in functionality\n        *   Change in implementation technique\n\n#### 4.7 Changes on Characteristics of System\n\nFour groups of changes:\n\n*   **Recode:**\n    *   Alters implementation properties by recoding the source program.\n    *   Uses rephrasing and program translation at the source code level.\n\n*   **Redesign:**\n    *   Common changes to software design include:\n        *   Restructuring the architecture.\n        *   Modifying the data model.\n        *   Replacing a procedure or algorithm with a more efficient one.\n\n*   **Respecify:**\n    *   Modifies the system\'s required characteristics by:\n        *   Changing the requirements\' form.\n        *   Changing the requirements\' scope.\n\n*   **Rethink:**\n    *   Changes the concepts embodied in an existing system to build a system that solves a different challenge.\n    *   Alters the system\'s conceptual properties and can fundamentally alter the system.\n\n#### 4.8 Software Re-Engineering Strategies\n\n*   **Rewrite Strategy:**\n    *   Reflects the principle of alteration.\n    *   An operational system is turned into a new system while maintaining the previous system\'s abstraction level.\n    *   Example: Rewriting Fortran code using the C language.\n\n*   **Rework Strategy:**\n    *   Applies all three principles: abstraction, alteration, and refinement.\n    *   Uses abstraction to create a less detailed representation.\n    *   Alters the rebuilt system model without changing the abstraction level.\n    *   Uses refinement to produce an acceptable new system representation at a lower level of abstraction.\n\n*   **Replace Strategy:**\n    *   Applies abstraction and refinement.\n    *   Hides details of a characteristic to reconstruct the system at a higher abstraction level.\n    *   Applies refinement to form an appropriate representation for the target system at a lower degree of abstraction.\n\n#### 4.9 Reengineering Process Variation\n\n*   **Key:** Understanding whether a target system can be produced based on starting abstraction level, type of changes, and strategy used.\n    *   **Yes:** A target system can be produced.\n    *   **Yes\\*:** Same as \"Yes,\" but the starting degree of abstraction is lower than the uppermost degree of abstraction within the conceptual abstraction level.\n    *   **No:** Cannot start at abstraction level A, make B type of changes, using strategy C, because the starting abstraction level is too high.\n    *   **Bad:** A target system can be created, but the likelihood of achieving a good result is low.\n\n#### 4.10 Re-Engineering Approaches\n\nTwo aspects are considered:\n1.  The extent of reengineering performed.\n2.  The rate of substitution of the operational system with the new one.\n\n##### 4.10.1 Big Bang Approach\n\n*   Replaces the entire system at the same time.\n*   Project continues until all objectives are met and the target system is built.\n*   Adopted when part-by-part reengineering isn\'t possible.\n\n##### 4.10.2 Incremental Approach\n\n*   The system is reengineered gradually, one step closer to the target system at a time.\n*   **Benefits:**\n    *   Easy detection of mistakes due to identifiable new components.\n    *   Easier for the client to detect progress through intermediate versions.\n    *   Less risky than the \"Big Bang\" method.\n*   **Disadvantages:**\n    *   Takes longer to complete due to multiple interim versions and careful version control.\n    *   The entire architecture of the system cannot be changed even if needed.\n\n##### 4.10.3 Partial Approach\n\n*   Only a part of the system is reengineered and then integrated with the non-engineered portion.\n*   **Steps:**\n    1.  Partition the existing system into two parts: one to be reengineered, the other not.\n    2.  Use either the \"Big Bang\" or \"Incremental\" approach to reengineer the chosen part.\n    3.  Combine the reengineered part and the non-reengineered part to form the new system.\n\n##### 4.10.4 Iterative Approach\n\n*   Reengineering is performed on the source code of a few procedures at a time, with each operation being short.\n*   This procedure is repeated on several components at different stages.\n\n##### 4.10.5 Evolutionary Approach\n\n*   Similar to the \"Incremental\" approach.\n*   Components of the original system are substituted with reengineered components.\n*   Existing components are grouped by functions and reengineered into new components.\n\n#### 4.11 Source Code Reengineering Reference Model (SCORE/RM)\n\n*   **Elements:**\n    *   Functions\n    *   Database repository\n    *   Documentation\n    *   Metrication\n*   **Purpose:** An approach to:\n    *   Understand the needs of the software.\n    *   Rationalize the system to be reengineered by eliminating redundant data and changing control flow.\n    *   Rebuild the software in accordance with best practices.\n\n##### 4.11.1 SCORE-RM Processes\n\n*(Visual representation from slide provided, outlining processes such as Analysis, Parsing, Transformation, Rationalization of Control Flow, Isolation, Normalization, Data Compression, Representation of Data, Interpretation, Functionalization, Programming Reading)*\n\n##### 4.11.2 Abstraction in SCORE-RM\n\n*(Visual representation from slide provided, outlining processes such as Identify Object Hierarchies, Separate operator from data, Group operators, Interpretation of object, Causation, Specify action, Specify software constraints, Regeneration, Generate detailed design, Create codes, Generate test cases, Certification, Conformance)*\n\n#### 4.12 Code Reverse Engineering\n\n*   **Definition:** A process to:\n    *   Define the components of operational software.\n    *   Define the interactions between those components.\n    *   Represent the system at a higher degree of abstraction or in another form.\n    *   Extracts information from current software artifacts and converts it into abstract models that maintenance people can understand.\n\n*   **Factors Necessitating Reverse Engineering:**\n    *   Original programmers have left the organization.\n    *   Implementation language has become obsolete, requiring migration.\n    *   Insufficient system documentation.\n    *   Business relies on software that is poorly understood.\n    *   Acquired system lacks full source code access.\n    *   System requires adaptations and/or enhancements.\n    *   Software does not operate as expected.\n\n#### 4.13 Reverse Engineering Techniques\n\n*   Lexical Analysis\n*   Syntactic Analysis\n*   Control Flow Analysis\n*   Data Flow Analysis\n*   Program Slicing\n*   Visualization\n*   Program Metrics\n\n##### 4.13.1 Lexical Analysis\n\n*   **Process:** Breaking down a source code sequence of characters into its constituent lexical units.\n*   Allows for various useful representations of program data.\n*   The cross-reference list is a commonly utilized program information.\n*   A lexical analyzer is a program that performs lexical analysis and is part of a compiler.\n\n##### 4.13.2 Syntactic Analysis\n\n*   **Process:** Performed by a parser.\n*   Uses context-free grammars, often expressed in Backus-Naur Form (BNF).\n*   Parsers can be built automatically from a description of a programming language\'s features.\n*   Example parsing tool: YACC (Yet Another Compiler Compiler).\n\n##### 4.13.3 Control Flow Analysis\n\n*   **Types:**\n    *   **Intra-procedural Analysis:**\n        *   Shows the order of statement execution within a subprogram.\n        *   Performed by generating Control Flow Graphs (CFGs) of subprograms.\n    *   **Inter-procedural Analysis:**\n        *   Performed by constructing a call graph.\n        *   Represents calling relationships between subroutines as a directed graph.\n\n##### 4.13.4 Data Flow Analysis (DFA)\n\n*   Concerns how values of defined variables flow through and are used in a program.\n*   Can detect the possibility of loops and data flow anomalies.\n*   Enables identification of:\n    *   Code that can never execute.\n    *   Variables used before they are defined.\n    *   Statements that might need alteration when a bug is fixed.\n\n##### 4.13.5 Program Slicing\n\n*   **Definition:** A program slice is a portion of a program with execution behavior identical to the original program concerning a given criterion, but potentially smaller.\n*   **Backward Slice:**\n    *   With respect to a variable `v` and a point `p`, it includes all instructions and predicates that affect the value of `v` at `p`.\n    *   Answers: \"What program components might affect a selected computation?\"\n*   **Forward Slicing:**\n    *   Includes all instructions and predicates that may depend on the value of `v` at `p`.\n    *   Answers: \"What program components might be affected by a selected computation?\"\n\n---\n\n#### References\n\n1.  Varga, E. (2017). *Unraveling software maintenance and evolution : thinking outside the box*. Springer.\n2.  Tsui, F., Karam, O., & Bernal, B. (2018). *Essentials of Software Engineering* (4th ed.). Jones & Bartlett Learning.\n3.  Tripathy, P., & Naik, K. (2014). *Software Evolution and Maintenance – A Practitioner’s Approach*. John Wiley and Son. Springer Vieweg.', 'user_upload/2/content/89e0bbcf-9807-4bd3-aec5-44bd173c6dbd.pdf', '2025-11-14');
