(40, 2, NULL, 'Chapter 3.pptx.pdf', 'pdf', '# BMSE3014 Software Maintenance\n\n## CHAPTER 3: SOFTWARE CONFIGURATION MANAGEMENT\n\n### 3.1 Introduction to Software Configuration Management (SCM)\n\n*   **Goal of CM:** To manage and control the numerous corrections, extensions, and adaptations that are applied to a system over its lifetime.\n*   **Scope:** It handles the control of all product items and changes to those items.\n*   **SCM Application:** Applied to software products, including documents, executable software, source code, hardware, and disks.\n\n### 3.2 Definition of Software Configuration Management\n\n*   **Definition:** The discipline of identifying the configuration of a system at discrete points in time for the purpose of systematically controlling changes to this configuration and maintaining the integrity and traceability of this configuration throughout the system life cycle.\n*   **Purpose:** Ensures a product\'s attributes remain consistent throughout its life cycle. It is an IT management technique that tracks individual configuration pieces of an IT system.\n*   **IT Assets:** IT systems are made up of a variety of IT assets with varying levels of granularity. A piece of software, a server, or a cluster of servers can all be considered IT assets. This chapter concentrates on configuration management as it relates to IT software assets and CI/CD.\n\n### 3.3 SCM Objectives and Impact\n\n*   **Traceability and Systematic Processes:** SCM ensures that development processes are traceable and systematic so that all changes are precisely managed, resulting in the product always being in a well-defined state.\n*   **Quality and Productivity:** SCM enhances the quality of the delivered system and the productivity of the maintainers.\n\n### 3.4 Key SCM Functions\n\n*   Uniquely identify every version of every software at various points in time.\n*   Retain past versions of documentation and software.\n*   Provide a trail of audit for all modifications performed.\n*   Throughout the software lifecycle, maintain the traceability and integrity of the system changes.\n\n### 3.5 Benefits of Software Configuration Management\n\n#### 3.5.1 General Benefits\n\n*   Confusion is reduced and order is established.\n*   Allows for the evaluation, approval, and implementation of changes into a configuration item in SCM.\n*   Organizes necessary activities to maintain product integrity.\n*   Ensures correct product configurations.\n*   Quality is ensured, leading to better quality software that consumes less maintenance effort.\n\n#### 3.5.2 Enhanced Benefits\n\n*   Productivity is improved as analysts and programmers know exactly where to find any piece of the software.\n*   Liability is reduced by documenting the trail of actions.\n*   Cost savings are realized across the product development life cycle.\n*   Maintaining product integrity through defined, tracked, and audited CIs ensures that the product released to customers has a well-managed bill of materials, enabling conformance with requirements.\n*   A reliable working environment is provided.\n*   Compliance with standards is enhanced.\n*   Accounting of status is enhanced.\n\n### 3.6 Four Elements of Configuration Management (CM)\n\n1.  **Identification of software configurations:** This includes the definitions of the different artifacts, their baselines or milestones, and the changes to the artifacts.\n2.  **Control of software configurations:** This element is about controlling the ways artifacts or configurations are altered with the necessary technical and administrative support.\n3.  **Auditing software configurations:** This element is about making the current status of the software system in its lifecycle visible to management and determining whether or not the baselines meet their requirements.\n4.  **Accounting software configuration status:** This element is about providing an administrative history of how the software system has been altered, by recording the activities necessitated by the other three SCM elements.\n\n### 3.7 Technical Dimension of SCM\n\n#### 3.7.1 Identification\n\n*   **Function:** Identifies the items whose configurations must be maintained.\n*   **Identified Elements:** Specification, design, documentation, data, drawings, source code, executable code, test plan, test script, hardware components, and software development environment components such as compilers, debuggers, and emulators.\n*   **Configuration Baseline:** The configuration baseline is identified.\n\n#### 3.7.2 Version Control\n\n*   **Mechanism:** Every time an artifact is modified, a new identifier is assigned to the artifact to minimize confusion during the evolution process.\n*   **Consideration:** Giving each alteration of the same artifact a new identification can obscure essential relationships between the objects that are individually recognized.\n\n#### 3.7.3 System Models and Selection\n\n*   **Defined Items:** Requirement specifications, test cases, design, code, test results, and defect reports are all examples of well-defined items in a project that are described in discrete files.\n*   **Aggregate Artifacts:** The requirement for aggregate artifacts develops so that maintenance employees can use linkages between artifacts and attributes to guarantee consistency in large projects.\n*   **Models:** Models that support the concept of software configurations are used to capture relationships between artifacts and attributes.\n*   **Configuration Definition:** A configuration, by definition, is a collection of versionable elements. The concept of configuration increases the necessity for users to be able to access sections and versions of aggregated artifacts selectively.\n\n#### 3.7.4 Workspace Control\n\n*   **Purpose:** SCM systems use work areas to provide users with a private location where they can undertake the standard responsibilities of editing and maintaining their objects.\n*   **Environment:** The workspace is the environment that allows the maintainer to make and test changes in a controlled environment.\n*   **Realization:** A workspace can be realized in two ways:\n    *   As basic as the programmer\'s home directory while modifying files.\n    *   A more complex system like an integrated development environment and a database.\n\n##### 3.7.4.1 Three Basic Functions in Workplace\n\n*   **Sandbox:** Checked-out files are placed in a workspace where they can be freely changed. The original files in the repository do not need to be locked.\n*   **Building:** To save space, an SCM system usually saves the differences between subsequent versions. As a result, the workspace converts the deltas into entire source files. The workspace also contains the derived binaries. SCM keeps track of source code (file) modifications (commits) and the revision history of each commit. The commits are compressed and will be enlarged (uncompressed/extracted) when the modifications for the specific commits are required. There are two types of repositories: a single repository and a distributed repository.\n*   **Isolation:** Each programmer has at least one workspace. As a result, the developer modifies the source code, compiles the files, tests the code, and debugs it without interfering with the work of other developers.\n\n#### 3.7.5 Building\n\n*   **Efficiency:** A key requirement of SCM systems is that developers can quickly build an executable file from the versioned source files.\n*   **Recovery and Testing:** SCM systems must enable the building of old versions of the system for recovery, testing, maintenance, or additional release purposes.\n*   **Support:** Most SCM systems support building of software.\n*   **Quality Assurance:** The build process and their products are assessed for quality assurance. Outputs of the build process become quality assurance records, and these records may be needed for future reference.\n\n#### 3.7.6 Change Management\n\n*   **SCM System Capabilities:** SCM systems must:\n    *   Enable users to understand the impact of modifications.\n    *   Enable users to identify the products to which a specific modification applies.\n    *   Provide maintenance personnel with tools for change management so that all activities from specifying requirements to coding can be traced.\n\n#### 3.7.7 Status Accounting\n\n*   **Purpose:** To quantify the properties of the software being developed and the process being used by gathering statistics at the SCM level.\n*   **Primary Objectives:**\n    *   Keep formal records of already existing configurations.\n    *   Produce periodic reports about the status of the configurations.\n*   **Record Functions:**\n    *   Describe the product correctly.\n    *   Are used to verify the configuration of the system for testing and delivery.\n    *   Maintain a history of CRs (Change Requests), including both approved and rejected ones.\n\n#### 3.7.8 Auditing\n\n*   **SCM System Features:** SCM systems need to provide the following features:\n    *   Return to prior stable points (Rollback).\n    *   Determine which alterations were made, why they were made, and who made them.\n*   **Types of Audits (before software release):**\n    *   **Audit for functional configuration:** Determines whether or not the software satisfies both user and system requirements.\n    *   **Audit for physical configuration:** Checks to see if the program is appropriately represented in the reference and design documentation.\n\n### 3.8 SCM Process\n\n#### 3.8.1 Establishing Baselines\n\n*   **Purpose:** To determine if something is subject to configuration management. Only a few instances have code, data, and documentation.\n*   **Software Baseline Library:** After configuration items have been identified, a software baseline library is constructed to make the list of changeable items publicly available.\n*   **Repository:** The library, also known as the repository, is at the heart of the SCM system. All public configurations are saved in the repository, which is a central location. The repository contains data on all of the things that have been baselined.\n\n#### 3.8.2 Baseline (or Re-baseline) Process Activities\n\n*   Create a snapshot of the current version of the product and its configuration elements, then assign the complete configuration a configuration identifier.\n*   Check in the configuration and assign version numbers to the configuration objects.\n*   Store the approved authority information as metadata in the repository.\n*   Distribute all of the following information to all stakeholders.\n*   Create a schema of words, numbers, or letters for common sorts of configuration objects to reliably identify the configuration version. Particular nomenclature may be required by project needs.\n\n#### 3.8.3 Controlling, Documenting, and Auditing\n\n*   **Post-Baseline Maintenance:** After establishing a baseline, it is important to maintain consistency between the actual and documented configurations, and ensure that the baseline corresponds with the project\'s requirements document configuration.\n*   **Regular Audits:** At regular intervals, records and products are audited to verify that:\n    *   There is an appropriate match between the documented and actual configurations.\n    *   The configuration complies with the project\'s criteria.\n    *   All change activity documentation is comprehensive and up-to-date.\n*   **Cyclical Nature:** Controlling, documenting, and auditing are the three steps in the cycle that are repeated throughout the project\'s life cycle.\n\n### 3.9 SCM Tools - Features\n\n#### 3.9.1 Version Control\n\n*   **Key Feature:** One of the key features offered by SCM tools is version control.\n*   **Mechanism:** These tools utilize an archiving method to save every change made to a file, allowing users to revert to a previous version if any issues arise. (Mentor, 2023)\n\n#### 3.9.2 Synchronization\n\n*   **Essential Feature:** Another essential feature of SCM tools is synchronization.\n*   **Functionality:** This allows users to check out multiple files or even a complete repository. After working on the necessary files, users can commit their changes back to the repository. Additionally, they can periodically update their local copies to reflect changes made by other team members, which is referred to as synchronization. (Mentor, 2023)\n\n#### 3.9.3 Concurrency Management\n\n*   **Definition:** Concurrency refers to the occurrence of multiple tasks simultaneously. In the context of SCM, it refers to different individuals editing the same file at the same time.\n*   **Importance:** If concurrency is not effectively managed with SCM tools, it can lead to significant issues. (Mentor, 2023)\n\n#### 3.9.4 Automation\n\n*   **Tasks Automated:** SCM tools decisively automate critical tasks such as building, testing, and deploying software.\n*   **Benefits:** This automation significantly reduces manual effort, boosts efficiency, and minimizes errors.\n*   **Examples:** Jenkins and TeamCity for build automation, while Ansible and Chef excel in automated deployments.\n\n#### 3.9.5 Dependency Mapping\n\n*   **Capability:** These tools effectively visualize and manage the relationships between different configuration items and services.\n*   **Importance:** This capability is essential for understanding the impact of changes and maintaining system health.\n\n### 3.10 SCM Tools – Examples\n\n*   Docker\n*   SolarWinds\n*   Octopus Deploy\n*   PowerShell\n*   ConfigHub\n\n### 3.11 References\n\n*   Blokdyk. G. (2020). Maintenance of software: a complete guide: practical tools for self-assessment. Art of Service.\n*   Blokdyk. G. (2020). Software change management: a complete guide: practical tools for self-assessment. Art of Service.\n*   Maxim. B. R., Pressman. R. S. (2020) Software Engineering: A Practitioner\'s Approach. 9th Edn. McGraw-Hill Education\n*   E. Varga. (2017). Unraveling software maintenance and evolution: thinking outside the box. Springer.\n*   F. Tsui. O. Karam. B. Bernal. (2018). Essentials of Software Engineering. 4th Edition. Jones & Bartlett Learning.\n*   Tripathy, P., Naik K. (2014). Software Evolution and Maintenance – A Practitioner’s Approach. John Wiley and Son. Springer Vieweg.\n*   Mentor, T. (2023, November 26). Features of Software Configuration Management - Software Testing Mentor. Software Testing Mentor. https://www.softwaretestingmentor.com/features-of-scm/\n*   Mentor, T. (2023, November 26). Features of Software Configuration Management - Software Testing Mentor. Software Testing Mentor. https://www.softwaretestingmentor.com/features-of-scm/', 'user_upload/2/content/19eb7ed5-8907-4603-9996-6672a9331eed.pdf', '2025-11-14'),
(41, 2, NULL, 'Chapter 2.pptx.pdf', 'pdf', '# BMSE3014 Software Maintenance\n\n## Chapter 2: Taxonomy of Software Maintenance\n\n### Key Characteristics of Maintenance Activities\n\n*   Keeping an eye on the software\'s day-to-day operations\n*   Keeping software changes under control\n*   Improve the software\'s current functions\n*   Threats to security are identified, and security flaws are fixed\n*   Preventing software performance from deteriorating to unacceptable levels\n\nSource: http://swebokwiki.org/Chapter_5:_Software_Maintenance\n\n### Characteristics of Software Maintenance\n\n#### Constraints of an Existing System\n\nOn an operational system, maintenance is carried out. As a result, all changes must be compatible with the existing software architecture, design, and code limitations.\n\n#### Shorter Time Frame\n\nMaintenance activities might last anywhere from a few hours to many months, but software creation can take up to a year.\n\n#### Available Test Data\n\nTest cases are created from scratch during software development, however software maintenance can choose a portion of these test cases and run them as regression tests. As a result, selecting acceptable test cases from the existing test suite is a hurdle. To effectively test the code changes, in addition to the regression test cases, new test cases must be written.\n\n### Intention-Based Classification\n\nAccording to ISO/IEC 14764, the categories of software maintenance are:\n\n*   Corrective\n*   Adaptive\n*   Perfective\n*   Preventive\n\nSource: http://swebokwiki.org/Chapter_5:_Software_Maintenance\n\n#### Corrective Maintenance\n\nReact to problems that are uncovered. Unplanned (unscheduled) software maintenance is also required to allow the software to function.\n\nSource: http://swebokwiki.org/Chapter_5:_Software_Maintenance\n\n#### Adaptive Maintenance\n\nMaintain software usability in an ever-changing environment. For example, software modifications may be required as a result of an operating system upgrade.\n\nSource: http://swebokwiki.org/Chapter_5:_Software_Maintenance\n\n#### Perfective Maintenance\n\nThe goal is to increase user experience, processing efficiency, and maintainability, among other things. For a better user experience, the program outputs can be made more understandable; the program can be updated to make it faster, hence enhancing processing efficiency.\n\nSource: http://swebokwiki.org/Chapter_5:_Software_Maintenance\n\n#### Preventive Maintenance\n\nAfter-sales modification of a software product to uncover and remedy fundamental flaws before they become operational flaws. For example, with good programming styles, the impact of change is reduced, thereby reducing the number of failures.\n\nSource: http://swebokwiki.org/Chapter_5:_Software_Maintenance\n\n### Activity-Based Classification\n\nThe intention of an activity depends upon the reason for the change. Two categories: corrections and enhancements.\n\n#### Corrections\n\nThe activities in this category are intended to correct system flaws, which are defined as a difference between the expected and actual behaviour of the system.\n\n|                 | Enhancement | Correction |\n| :-------------- | :---------- | :--------- |\n| Proactive       | Perfective  | Preventive |\n| Reactive        | Adaptive    | Corrective |\n\nSource from: Tripathy, P., Naik K. (2014). Software Evolution and Maintenance – A Practitioner’s Approach. John Wiley and Son. Springer Vieweg.\n\n#### Enhancements\n\nDo not necessarily modify the system’s behavior. Categorised into three subcategories as follows:\n\n*   Enhancement activities that modify existing requirements (some) implemented by the system\n*   Enhancement activities that add new system requirements; and\n*   Enhancement activities that change the implementation without modifying the existing requirements of the system.\n\n|                 | Enhancement | Correction |\n| :-------------- | :---------- | :--------- |\n| Proactive       | Perfective  | Preventive |\n| Reactive        | Adaptive    | Corrective |\n\nSource from: Tripathy, P., Naik K. (2014). Software Evolution and Maintenance – A Practitioner’s Approach. John Wiley and Son. Springer Vieweg.\n\n### Evidence-Based Classification\n\n#### Objectives\n\n*   Based on objective evidence, which may be measured by observations and comparisons of software before and after alterations\n*   Select the classification coarseness to reflect a true representative mix of observed activities\n*   Hardware, operating system (OS), organisational processes, design methodology, implementation language, and employees involved in maintenance should all be classified independently of the execution and development environments.\n\nSource from: Tripathy, P., Naik K. (2014). Software Evolution and Maintenance – A Practitioner’s Approach. John Wiley and Son. Springer Vieweg.\n\n#### Classification of Maintenance Activities\n\nThe types of maintenance activities are clustered based on modifications made, detected, or observed on four elements of the system being maintained:\n\n*   The entire software\n*   The external documentation\n*   The properties of the program code\n*   The experience of customer on system functionality.\n\nSource from: Tripathy, P., Naik K. (2014). Software Evolution and Maintenance – A Practitioner’s Approach. John Wiley and Son. Springer Vieweg.\n\n### Support Interface\n\n#### Training\n\nThis refers to informing the stakeholders about the system\'s implementation.\n\n#### Consultive\n\nIn this type, maintenance work is estimated in terms of cost and time, personnel staff a help desk, clients are assisted in preparing maintenance work requests, and personnel share expert knowledge of available resources and the system with others in the company to improve efficiency.\n\n#### Evaluative\n\nReviewing the program code and documentations, assessing the ripple effect of a proposed modification, writing and performing tests, examining the programming support offered by the operating system, and discovering and debugging the required data are all common actions in this kind.\n\nSource from: Tripathy, P., Naik K. (2014). Software Evolution and Maintenance – A Practitioner’s Approach. John Wiley and Son. Springer Vieweg.\n\n### Documentation\n\n#### Reformative\n\nOrdinary actions of this sort include improving the readability of the documentation, aligning it with other system modifications, creating training materials, and adding entries to a data dictionary.\n\n#### Updative\n\nTypical tasks include replacing out-of-date documentation with current documentation, creating semi-formal documentation, such as in UML, to document current programme code, and updating the documentation with test plans.\n\nSource from: Tripathy, P., Naik K. (2014). Software Evolution and Maintenance – A Practitioner’s Approach. John Wiley and Son. Springer Vieweg.\n\n### Software Properties\n\n#### Groomative\n\nSubstituting more efficient and simpler components and algorithms, updating data naming standards, changing access authorizations, compiling source code, and performing backups are all common actions in this category. Ordinary preventive efforts of this type make improvements to improve maintainability and lay the groundwork for a future transition to an emerging technology. Performance activities provide results that have an influence on the user. These operations increase system uptime by replacing slower components and algorithms. Ordinary Adaptive actions of this sort migrate software to a new execution platform and increase the use of COTS components.\n\nSource from: Tripathy, P., Naik K. (2014). Software Evolution and Maintenance – A Practitioner’s Approach. John Wiley and Son. Springer Vieweg.\n\n### Business Rules\n\n#### Reductive\n\nOrdinary operations of this sort reduce the amount of data input to the system and reduce the amount of data created by the system.\n\n#### Corrective\n\nCorrecting detected flaws, implementing defensive programming strategies, and changing the way exceptions are handled are all common actions in this category.\n\n#### Enhancive\n\nAdding and changing business rules to improve the system\'s functionality available to the client, as well as adding new data flows into or out of the software, are typical tasks in this category.\n\nSource from: Tripathy, P., Naik K. (2014). Software Evolution and Maintenance – A Practitioner’s Approach. John Wiley and Son. Springer Vieweg.\n\n### Evidence-Based Maintenance Activities\n\nSource from: Tripathy, P., Naik K. (2014). Software Evolution and and Maintenance – A Practitioner’s Approach. John Wiley and Son. Springer Vieweg.\n\n### Evidence-Based Classification: Decision Tree-Based Criteria\n\nSource from: Tripathy, P., Naik K. (2014). Software Evolution and Maintenance – A Practitioner’s Approach. John Wiley and Son. Springer Vieweg.\n\n## Issues and Challenges in Software Maintenance\n\nSource: Gupta et al., n.d.\n\n### Costs\n\nSoftware maintenance is a big part of the overall development process, consuming between 60% and 80% of total costs. Most of these expenses come from making enhancements or updates to the software rather than fixing errors.\n\n### Impact Analysis\n\nOne major challenge in maintaining software is understanding how changes will affect the rest of the system. Impact analysis helps assess the possible outcomes of a modification, aiming to minimize unexpected problems. This process includes checking if the proposed change is correct, evaluating risks, and estimating how it will impact system performance and development.\n\n### Corrective Changes\n\nCorrective changes can be tricky because it\'s often hard to identify where exactly changes need to be made in the code. Recognizing the relevant parts of the codebase can be difficult. Even small modifications might require significant changes to the software\'s structure, which can be time-consuming. If a workaround has already been implemented for a problem, fixing new issues can become even more complicated. Repairing design flaws is challenging since it requires a deep understanding of the entire codebase and comes with risks.\n\n### Adaptive Changes\n\nAdaptive changes, which involve updating the software to work with new technologies, can also be hard. Sometimes, there\'s not enough information about what the software needs to change to. Understanding new technologies and how to integrate them can be difficult. Additionally, issues may arise from a lack of proper initial design.\n\n### Program Comprehension\n\nProgram comprehension is another important aspect. Maintenance engineers often spend a lot of time reading and understanding the code and documentation to grasp the logic, purpose, and structure of the software. This understanding is crucial for effectively maintaining and improving the quality of the software.\n\n## IEEE Maintenance Process (IEEE 1219)\n\nSource: Tripathy, P., Naik K. (2014). Software Evolution and Maintenance – A Practitioner’s Approach. John Wiley and Son. Springer Vieweg\n\n*   Problem Identification & Classification\n*   Request\n*   Analysis\n*   Design\n*   Implementation\n*   System Test\n*   Acceptance Test\n*   Delivery\n\n### IEEE Maintenance Process Attributes\n\nEach of the seven activities have five associated attributes as follows:\n\n*   **Activity definition:** This refers to the implementation process of the activity.\n*   **Input:** This refers to the items that are required as input to the activity.\n*   **Output:** This refers to the items that are produced by the activity.\n*   **Control:** This refers to those items that provide control over the activity.\n*   **Metrics:** This refers to the items that are measured during the execution of the activity.\n\nSource: Tripathy, P., Naik K. (2014). Software Evolution and Maintenance – A Practitioner’s Approach. John Wiley and Son. Springer Vieweg.\n\n## ISO/IEC 14764 Maintenance Process\n\nAbran, Alain & Moore, James & Bourque, Pierre & Dupuis, Robert. (2001). Guide to the Software Engineering Body of Knowledge - Trial Version (Version 0,9).\n\n### ISO/IEC 14764 Maintenance Process High-Level Activities\n\nThe maintenance process comprises the following high-level activities:\n\n1.  Process implementation\n2.  Problem and modification analysis\n3.  Modification implementation\n4.  Maintenance review and acceptance\n5.  Migration\n6.  Retirement\n\nAbran, Alain & Moore, James & Bourque, Pierre & Dupuis, Robert. (2001). Guide to the Software Engineering Body of Knowledge - Trial Version (Version 0,9).\n\n#### Process Implementation\n\n*   Create maintenance processes and strategies.\n*   Procedures for Modification Requests should be established.\n*   Put the CM process into action.\n\nSource: Tripathy, P., Naik K. (2014). Software Evolution and Maintenance – A Practitioner’s Approach. John Wiley and Son. Springer Vieweg.\n\n#### Problem and Modification Analysis\n\n*   Perform a preliminary investigation.\n*   Confirm the issue.\n*   Create choices for executing the change.\n*   Keep track of the outcomes.\n*   Obtain clearance for the option of modification.\n\nSource: Tripathy, P., Naik K. (2014). Software Evolution and Maintenance – A Practitioner’s Approach. John Wiley and Son. Springer Vieweg.\n\n#### Implement Modification\n\n*   Conduct a thorough investigation (analysis).\n*   The modification should be developed, coded, and tested.\n\nSource: Tripathy, P., Naik K. (2014). Software Evolution and Maintenance – A Practitioner’s Approach. John Wiley and Son. Springer Vieweg.\n\n#### Maintenance Review and Acceptance\n\n*   Conduct evaluations.\n*   Obtain approval for the change.\n\nSource: Tripathy, P., Naik K. (2014). Software Evolution and Maintenance – A Practitioner’s Approach. John Wiley and Son. Springer Vieweg.\n\n#### Migration\n\n*   Ascertain that the migration is compliant with ISO/IEC 12207.\n*   Make a migration strategy.\n*   Users should be notified about migration intentions.\n*   Carry out processes in parallel.\n*   Notify the user that the transfer has begun.\n*   Conduct a post-op evaluation.\n*   Make sure that old data can be accessed.\n\nSource: Tripathy, P., Naik K. (2014). Software Evolution and Maintenance – A Practitioner’s Approach. John Wiley and Son. Springer Vieweg.\n\n#### Retirement\n\n*   Develop a plan for retirement.\n*   Acknowledge users of retirement plans.\n*   Parallel operations are conducted.\n*   Acknowledge user the start of retirement.\n*   Make sure old data is accessible.\n\nSource: Tripathy, P., Naik K. (2014). Software Evolution and Maintenance – A Practitioner’s Approach. John Wiley and Son. Springer Vieweg.\n\n## Maintenance Models\n\n### Reuse-Oriented Models\n\n1.  Quick fix model\n2.  Iterative enhancement model\n3.  Full reuse model\n\nSource: Tripathy, P., Naik K. (2014). Software Evolution and Maintenance – A Practitioner’s Approach. John Wiley and Son. Springer Vieweg.\n\n### Reuse-Oriented Models\n\nAssumes that existing components can be re-used in software maintenance. It consists of the following steps:\n\n*   Identifying the components of the old system which can be reused\n*   Understanding these components\n*   Modifying the old system components so that they can be used in the new system\n*   Integrating the modified components into the new system.\n\nSource: http://www.professionalqa.com/software-maintenance-models\nSource: Tripathy, P., Naik K. (2014). Software Evolution and Maintenance – A Practitioner’s Approach. John Wiley and Son. Springer Vieweg.\n\n#### Quick Fix Model\n\nSource: http://www.professionalqa.com/software-maintenance-models\n\n##### Quick Fix Model Description\n\n*   Necessary changes are quickly made to the code and then to the accompanying documentation.\n*   The new code is recompiled to produce a new version.\n*   Embodies a commonly used approach to software maintenance.\n*   Low cost.\n*   Less concern on the impacts of modifications.\n\nSource: http://www.professionalqa.com/software-maintenance-models\n\n#### Iterative Enhancement Model\n\nSource: http://www.professionalqa.com/software-maintenance-models\n\n##### Iterative Enhancement Model Description\n\n*   Based on the Japanese concept of Kaizen, which stands for the gradual and systematic enhancement of procedures.\n*   First changes are made to the highest level documents.\n*   Eventually, changes are propagated down to the code level.\n*   Assumes complete documentation is available.\n*   It begins with the existing system’s artifacts, namely, requirements, design, code, test, and analysis documents.\n*   It revises the highest-level documents affected by the changes and propagates the changes down through the lower-level documents.\n*   The model allows maintainers to redesign the system, based on the analysis of the existing system.\n*   Also accommodates the quick fix model.\n\nThree stages cycle:\n\n*   Analysis of software system.\n*   Classification of requested modifications.\n*   Implementation of requested modifications.\n\nSource: http://www.professionalqa.com/software-maintenance-models\n\n#### Full Reuse Model\n\n*   A new system is built from components of the old system and others available in the repository.\n*   The main assumption in this model is the availability of a repository of artifacts describing the earlier versions of the present and similar systems.\n\nSource: Tripathy, P., Naik K. (2014). Software Evolution and Maintenance – A Practitioner’s Approach. John Wiley and Son. Springer Vieweg.\n\n##### Full Reuse Model Activities\n\nFull reuse comprises two major steps:\n\n1.  Perform requirement analysis and design of the new system.\n2.  Use the appropriate artifacts, such as requirements, design, code, and test from any earlier versions of the old system.\n\nThe following activities are performed:\n\n*   Identify the components of the old system that are candidates for reuse.\n*   Understand the identified system components.\n*   Modify the old system components to support the new requirements.\n*   Integrate the modified components to form the newly developed system.\n\nSource: Tripathy, P., Naik K. (2014). Software Evolution and Maintenance – A Practitioner’s Approach. John Wiley and Son. Springer Vieweg.\n\n### Other Models\n\n*   Boehm\'s Model\n*   Taute Maintenance Model.\n\nSource: http://www.professionalqa.com/software-maintenance-models\n\n## References\n\n1.  Blokdyk. G. (2020). *Maintenance of software: a complete guide: practical tools for self-assessment*. Art of Service.\n2.  Blokdyk. G. (2020). *Software change management: a complete guide: practical tools for self-assessment*. Art of Service.\n3.  Maxim. B. R., Pressman. R. S. (2020) *Software Engineering: A Practitioner\'s Approach*. 9th Edn. McGraw-Hill Education.\n4.  E. Varga. (2017). *Unraveling software maintenance and evolution: thinking outside the box*. Springer.\n5.  F. Tsui. O. Karam. B. Bernal. (2018). *Essentials of Software Engineering*. 4th Edition. Jones & Bartlett Learning.\n6.  Tripathy, P., Naik K. (2014). *Software Evolution and Maintenance – A Practitioner’s Approach*. John Wiley and Son. Springer Vieweg.\n7.  Abran, Alain & Moore, James & Bourque, Pierre & Dupuis, Robert. (2001). *Guide to the Software Engineering Body of Knowledge - Trial Version (Version 0,9)*. 10.13140/RG.2.2.12202.44489.\n8.  Gupta, A., Xavier, S., & Sharma, S. (n.d.). Software Maintenance: Challenges and Issues. https://www.ijcse.net/docs/IJCSE15-04-01-037.pdf', 'user_upload/2/content/b9a91b8e-b376-45d8-91da-467daa3fbfdd.pdf', '2025-11-14'),
