(40, 41, '{\"markdown\":\"# BMSE3014 Software Maintenance\\n\\n## Chapter 2: Taxonomy of Software Maintenance\\n\\n### Key Characteristics of Maintenance Activities\\n\\n#### Monitoring Operations\\n\\n*Keeping an eye on the software\'s day-to-day operations.*\\n\\n#### Change Control\\n\\n*Keeping software changes under control.*\\n\\n#### Functional Improvement\\n\\n*Improve the software\'s current functions.*\\n\\n#### Security Patching\\n\\n*Threats to security are identified, and security flaws are fixed.*\\n\\n#### Performance Preservation\\n\\n*Preventing software performance from deteriorating to unacceptable levels.*\\n\\nSource: http:\\/\\/swebokwiki.org\\/Chapter_5:_Software_Maintenance\\n\\n### Characteristics of Software Maintenance\\n\\n#### Constraints of an Existing System\\n\\n*On an operational system, maintenance is carried out. As a result, all changes must be compatible with the existing software architecture, design, and code limitations.*\\n\\n#### Shorter Time Frame\\n\\n*Maintenance activities might last anywhere from a few hours to many months, but software creation can take up to a year.*\\n\\n#### Available Test Data\\n\\n*Test cases are created from scratch during software development, however software maintenance can choose a portion of these test cases and run them as regression tests. As a result, selecting acceptable test cases from the existing test suite is a hurdle. To effectively test the code changes, in addition to the regression test cases, new test cases must be written.*\\n\\n### Intention-Based Classification\\n\\nAccording to ISO\\/IEC 14764, the categories of software maintenance are:\\n\\n#### Corrective Maintenance\\n\\n*React to problems that are uncovered. Unplanned (unscheduled) software maintenance is also required to allow the software to function.*\\n\\nSource: http:\\/\\/swebokwiki.org\\/Chapter_5:_Software_Maintenance\\n\\n#### Adaptive Maintenance\\n\\n*Maintain software usability in an ever-changing environment. For example, software modifications may be required as a result of an operating system upgrade.*\\n\\nSource: http:\\/\\/swebokwiki.org\\/Chapter_5:_Software_Maintenance\\n\\n#### Perfective Maintenance\\n\\n*The goal is to increase user experience, processing efficiency, and maintainability, among other things. For a better user experience, the program outputs can be made more understandable; the program can be updated to make it faster, hence enhancing processing efficiency.*\\n\\nSource: http:\\/\\/swebokwiki.org\\/Chapter_5:_Software_Maintenance\\n\\n#### Preventive Maintenance\\n\\n*After-sales modification of a software product to uncover and remedy fundamental flaws before they become operational flaws. For example, with good programming styles, the impact of change is reduced, thereby reducing the number of failures.*\\n\\nSource: http:\\/\\/swebokwiki.org\\/Chapter_5:_Software_Maintenance\\n\\n### Activity-Based Classification\\n\\nThe intention of an activity depends upon the reason for the change. Two categories: corrections and enhancements.\\n\\n#### Corrections\\n\\n*The activities in this category are intended to correct system flaws, which are defined as a difference between the expected and actual behaviour of the system.*\\n\\n|                 | Enhancement | Correction |\\n| :-------------- | :---------- | :--------- |\\n| Proactive       | Perfective  | Preventive |\\n| Reactive        | Adaptive    | Corrective |\\n\\nSource from: Tripathy, P., Naik K. (2014). *Software Evolution and Maintenance – A Practitioner’s Approach*. John Wiley and Son. Springer Vieweg.\\n\\n#### Enhancements\\n\\n*Do not necessarily modify the system’s behavior. Categorised into three subcategories as follows:*\\n\\n*   *Enhancement activities that modify existing requirements (some) implemented by the system*\\n*   *Enhancement activities that add new system requirements; and*\\n*   *Enhancement activities that change the implementation without modifying the existing requirements of the system.*\\n\\n|                 | Enhancement | Correction |\\n| :-------------- | :---------- | :--------- |\\n| Proactive       | Perfective  | Preventive |\\n| Reactive        | Adaptive    | Corrective |\\n\\nSource from: Tripathy, P., Naik K. (2014). *Software Evolution and Maintenance – A Practitioner’s Approach*. John Wiley and Son. Springer Vieweg.\\n\\n### Evidence-Based Classification\\n\\n#### Objectives\\n\\n*   *Based on objective evidence, which may be measured by observations and comparisons of software before and after alterations*\\n*   *Select the classification coarseness to reflect a true representative mix of observed activities*\\n*   *Hardware, operating system (OS), organisational processes, design methodology, implementation language, and employees involved in maintenance should all be classified independently of the execution and development environments.*\\n\\nSource from: Tripathy, P., Naik K. (2014). *Software Evolution and Maintenance – A Practitioner’s Approach*. John Wiley and Son. Springer Vieweg.\\n\\n#### Classification of Maintenance Activities\\n\\n*The types of maintenance activities are clustered based on modifications made, detected, or observed on four elements of the system being maintained:*\\n\\n*   *The entire software*\\n*   *The external documentation*\\n*   *The properties of the program code*\\n*   *The experience of customer on system functionality.*\\n\\nSource from: Tripathy, P., Naik K. (2014). *Software Evolution and Maintenance – A Practitioner’s Approach*. John Wiley and Son. Springer Vieweg.\\n\\n### Support Interface\\n\\n#### Training\\n\\n*This refers to informing the stakeholders about the system\'s implementation.*\\n\\n#### Consultive\\n\\n*In this type, maintenance work is estimated in terms of cost and time, personnel staff a help desk, clients are assisted in preparing maintenance work requests, and personnel share expert knowledge of available resources and the system with others in the company to improve efficiency.*\\n\\n#### Evaluative\\n\\n*Reviewing the program code and documentations, assessing the ripple effect of a proposed modification, writing and performing tests, examining the programming support offered by the operating system, and discovering and debugging the required data are all common actions in this kind.*\\n\\nSource from: Tripathy, P., Naik K. (2014). *Software Evolution and Maintenance – A Practitioner’s Approach*. John Wiley and Son. Springer Vieweg.\\n\\n### Documentation\\n\\n#### Reformative\\n\\n*Ordinary actions of this sort include improving the readability of the documentation, aligning it with other system modifications, creating training materials, and adding entries to a data dictionary.*\\n\\n#### Updative\\n\\n*Typical tasks include replacing out-of-date documentation with current documentation, creating semi-formal documentation, such as in UML, to document current programme code, and updating the documentation with test plans.*\\n\\nSource from: Tripathy, P., Naik K. (2014). *Software Evolution and Maintenance – A Practitioner’s Approach*. John Wiley and Son. Springer Vieweg.\\n\\n### Software Properties\\n\\n#### Groomative\\n\\n*Substituting more efficient and simpler components and algorithms, updating data naming standards, changing access authorizations, compiling source code, and performing backups are all common actions in this category. Ordinary preventive efforts of this type make improvements to improve maintainability and lay the groundwork for a future transition to an emerging technology. Performance activities provide results that have an influence on the user. These operations increase system uptime by replacing slower components and algorithms. Ordinary Adaptive actions of this sort migrate software to a new execution platform and increase the use of COTS components.*\\n\\nSource from: Tripathy, P., Naik K. (2014). *Software Evolution and Maintenance – A Practitioner’s Approach*. John Wiley and Son. Springer Vieweg.\\n\\n### Business Rules\\n\\n#### Reductive\\n\\n*Ordinary operations of this sort reduce the amount of data input to the system and reduce the amount of data created by the system.*\\n\\n#### Corrective\\n\\n*Correcting detected flaws, implementing defensive programming strategies, and changing the way exceptions are handled are all common actions in this category.*\\n\\n#### Enhancive\\n\\n*Adding and changing business rules to improve the system\'s functionality available to the client, as well as adding new data flows into or out of the software, are typical tasks in this category.*\\n\\nSource from: Tripathy, P., Naik K. (2014). *Software Evolution and Maintenance – A Practitioner’s Approach*. John Wiley and Son. Springer Vieweg.\\n\\n### Evidence-Based Maintenance Activities\\n\\nSource from: Tripathy, P., Naik K. (2014). *Software Evolution and and Maintenance – A Practitioner’s Approach*. John Wiley and Son. Springer Vieweg.\\n\\n### Evidence-Based Classification: Decision Tree-Based Criteria\\n\\nSource from: Tripathy, P., Naik K. (2014). *Software Evolution and Maintenance – A Practitioner’s Approach*. John Wiley and Son. Springer Vieweg.\\n\\n## Issues and Challenges in Software Maintenance\\n\\nSource: Gupta et al., n.d.\\n\\n### Costs\\n\\n*Software maintenance is a big part of the overall development process, consuming between 60% and 80% of total costs. Most of these expenses come from making enhancements or updates to the software rather than fixing errors.*\\n\\n### Impact Analysis\\n\\n*One major challenge in maintaining software is understanding how changes will affect the rest of the system. Impact analysis helps assess the possible outcomes of a modification, aiming to minimize unexpected problems. This process includes checking if the proposed change is correct, evaluating risks, and estimating how it will impact system performance and development.*\\n\\n### Corrective Changes\\n\\n*Corrective changes can be tricky because it\'s often hard to identify where exactly changes need to be made in the code. Recognizing the relevant parts of the codebase can be difficult. Even small modifications might require significant changes to the software\'s structure, which can be time-consuming. If a workaround has already been implemented for a problem, fixing new issues can become even more complicated. Repairing design flaws is challenging since it requires a deep understanding of the entire codebase and comes with risks.*\\n\\n### Adaptive Changes\\n\\n*Adaptive changes, which involve updating the software to work with new technologies, can also be hard. Sometimes, there\'s not enough information about what the software needs to change to. Understanding new technologies and how to integrate them can be difficult. Additionally, issues may arise from a lack of proper initial design.*\\n\\n### Program Comprehension\\n\\n*Program comprehension is another important aspect. Maintenance engineers often spend a lot of time reading and understanding the code and documentation to grasp the logic, purpose, and structure of the software. This understanding is crucial for effectively maintaining and improving the quality of the software.*\\n\\n## IEEE Maintenance Process (IEEE 1219)\\n\\nSource: Tripathy, P., Naik K. (2014). *Software Evolution and Maintenance – A Practitioner’s Approach*. John Wiley and Son. Springer Vieweg\\n\\n*   Problem Identification & Classification\\n*   Request\\n*   Analysis\\n*   Design\\n*   Implementation\\n*   System Test\\n*   Acceptance Test\\n*   Delivery\\n\\n### IEEE Maintenance Process Attributes\\n\\n*Each of the seven activities have five associated attributes as follows:*\\n\\n*   **Activity definition:** *This refers to the implementation process of the activity.*\\n*   **Input:** *This refers to the items that are required as input to the activity.*\\n*   **Output:** *This refers to the items that are produced by the activity.*\\n*   **Control:** *This refers to those items that provide control over the activity.*\\n*   **Metrics:** *This refers to the items that are measured during the execution of the activity.*\\n\\nSource: Tripathy, P., Naik K. (2014). *Software Evolution and Maintenance – A Practitioner’s Approach*. John Wiley and Son. Springer Vieweg.\\n\\n## ISO\\/IEC 14764 Maintenance Process\\n\\nAbran, Alain & Moore, James & Bourque, Pierre & Dupuis, Robert. (2001). *Guide to the Software Engineering Body of Knowledge - Trial Version (Version 0,9)*.\\n\\n### ISO\\/IEC 14764 Maintenance Process High-Level Activities\\n\\n*The maintenance process comprises the following high-level activities:*\\n\\n1.  Process implementation\\n2.  Problem and modification analysis\\n3.  Modification implementation\\n4.  Maintenance review and acceptance\\n5.  Migration\\n6.  Retirement\\n\\nAbran, Alain & Moore, James & Bourque, Pierre & Dupuis, Robert. (2001). *Guide to the Software Engineering Body of Knowledge - Trial Version (Version 0,9)*.\\n\\n#### Process Implementation\\n\\n*   *Create maintenance processes and strategies.*\\n*   *Procedures for Modification Requests should be established.*\\n*   *Put the CM process into action.*\\n\\nSource: Tripathy, P., Naik K. (2014). *Software Evolution and Maintenance – A Practitioner’s Approach*. John Wiley and Son. Springer Vieweg.\\n\\n#### Problem and Modification Analysis\\n\\n*   *Perform a preliminary investigation.*\\n*   *Confirm the issue.*\\n*   *Create choices for executing the change.*\\n*   *Keep track of the outcomes.*\\n*   *Obtain clearance for the option of modification.*\\n\\nSource: Tripathy, P., Naik K. (2014). *Software Evolution and Maintenance – A Practitioner’s Approach*. John Wiley and Son. Springer Vieweg.\\n\\n#### Implement Modification\\n\\n*   *Conduct a thorough investigation (analysis).*\\n*   *The modification should be developed, coded, and tested.*\\n\\nSource: Tripathy, P., Naik K. (2014). *Software Evolution and Maintenance – A Practitioner’s Approach*. John Wiley and Son. Springer Vieweg.\\n\\n#### Maintenance Review and Acceptance\\n\\n*   *Conduct evaluations.*\\n*   *Obtain approval for the change.*\\n\\nSource: Tripathy, P., Naik K. (2014). *Software Evolution and Maintenance – A Practitioner’s Approach*. John Wiley and Son. Springer Vieweg.\\n\\n#### Migration\\n\\n*   *Ascertain that the migration is compliant with ISO\\/IEC 12207.*\\n*   *Make a migration strategy.*\\n*   *Users should be notified about migration intentions.*\\n*   *Carry out processes in parallel.*\\n*   *Notify the user that the transfer has begun.*\\n*   *Conduct a post-op evaluation.*\\n*   *Make sure that old data can be accessed.*\\n\\nSource: Tripathy, P., Naik K. (2014). *Software Evolution and Maintenance – A Practitioner’s Approach*. John Wiley and Son. Springer Vieweg.\\n\\n#### Retirement\\n\\n*   *Develop a plan for retirement.*\\n*   *Acknowledge users of retirement plans.*\\n*   *Parallel operations are conducted.*\\n*   *Acknowledge user the start of retirement.*\\n*   *Make sure old data is accessible.*\\n\\nSource: Tripathy, P., Naik K. (2014). *Software Evolution and Maintenance – A Practitioner’s Approach*. John Wiley and Son. Springer Vieweg.\\n\\n## Maintenance Models\\n\\n### Reuse-Oriented Models\\n\\n1.  Quick fix model\\n2.  Iterative enhancement model\\n3.  Full reuse model\\n\\nSource: Tripathy, P., Naik K. (2014). *Software Evolution and Maintenance – A Practitioner’s Approach*. John Wiley and Son. Springer Vieweg.\\n\\n### Reuse-Oriented Models\\n\\n*Assumes that existing components can be re-used in software maintenance. It consists of the following steps:*\\n\\n*   *Identifying the components of the old system which can be reused*\\n*   *Understanding these components*\\n*   *Modifying the old system components so that they can be used in the new system*\\n*   *Integrating the modified components into the new system.*\\n\\nSource: http:\\/\\/www.professionalqa.com\\/software-maintenance-models\\nSource: Tripathy, P., Naik K. (2014). *Software Evolution and Maintenance – A Practitioner’s Approach*. John Wiley and Son. Springer Vieweg.\\n\\n#### Quick Fix Model\\n\\nSource: http:\\/\\/www.professionalqa.com\\/software-maintenance-models\\n\\n##### Quick Fix Model Description\\n\\n*   *Necessary changes are quickly made to the code and then to the accompanying documentation.*\\n*   *The new code is recompiled to produce a new version.*\\n*   *Embodies a commonly used approach to software maintenance.*\\n*   *Low cost.*\\n*   *Less concern on the impacts of modifications.*\\n\\nSource: http:\\/\\/www.professionalqa.com\\/software-maintenance-models\\n\\n#### Iterative Enhancement Model\\n\\nSource: http:\\/\\/www.professionalqa.com\\/software-maintenance-models\\n\\n##### Iterative Enhancement Model Description\\n\\n*   *Based on the Japanese concept of Kaizen, which stands for the gradual and systematic enhancement of procedures.*\\n*   *First changes are made to the highest level documents.*\\n*   *Eventually, changes are propagated down to the code level.*\\n*   *Assumes complete documentation is available.*\\n*   *It begins with the existing system’s artifacts, namely, requirements, design, code, test, and analysis documents.*\\n*   *It revises the highest-level documents affected by the changes and propagates the changes down through the lower-level documents.*\\n*   *The model allows maintainers to redesign the system, based on the analysis of the existing system.*\\n*   *Also accommodates the quick fix model.*\\n\\nThree stages cycle:\\n\\n*   *Analysis of software system.*\\n*   *Classification of requested modifications.*\\n*   *Implementation of requested modifications.*\\n\\nSource: http:\\/\\/www.professionalqa.com\\/software-maintenance-models\\n\\n#### Full Reuse Model\\n\\n*   *A new system is built from components of the old system and others available in the repository.*\\n*   *The main assumption in this model is the availability of a repository of artifacts describing the earlier versions of the present and similar systems.*\\n\\nSource: Tripathy, P., Naik K. (2014). *Software Evolution and Maintenance – A Practitioner’s Approach*. John Wiley and Son. Springer Vieweg.\\n\\n##### Full Reuse Model Activities\\n\\n*Full reuse comprises two major steps:*\\n\\n1.  *Perform requirement analysis and design of the new system.*\\n2.  *Use the appropriate artifacts, such as requirements, design, code, and test from any earlier versions of the old system.*\\n\\nThe following activities are performed:\\n\\n*   *Identify the components of the old system that are candidates for reuse.*\\n*   *Understand the identified system components.*\\n*   *Modify the old system components to support the new requirements.*\\n*   *Integrate the modified components to form the newly developed system.*\\n\\nSource: Tripathy, P., Naik K. (2014). *Software Evolution and Maintenance – A Practitioner’s Approach*. John Wiley and Son. Springer Vieweg.\\n\\n### Other Models\\n\\n*   Boehm\'s Model\\n*   Taute Maintenance Model.\\n\\nSource: http:\\/\\/www.professionalqa.com\\/software-maintenance-models\\n\\n## References\\n\\n1.  Blokdyk. G. (2020). *Maintenance of software: a complete guide: practical tools for self-assessment*. Art of Service.\\n2.  Blokdyk. G. (2020). *Software change management: a complete guide: practical tools for self-assessment*. Art of Service.\\n3.  Maxim. B. R., Pressman. R. S. (2020) *Software Engineering: A Practitioner\'s Approach*. 9th Edn. McGraw-Hill Education.\\n4.  E. Varga. (2017). *Unraveling software maintenance and evolution: thinking outside the box*. Springer.\\n5.  F. Tsui. O. Karam. B. Bernal. (2018). *Essentials of Software Engineering*. 4th Edition. Jones & Bartlett Learning.\\n6.  Tripathy, P., Naik K. (2014). *Software Evolution and Maintenance – A Practitioner’s Approach*. John Wiley and Son. Springer Vieweg.\\n7.  Abran, Alain & Moore, James & Bourque, Pierre & Dupuis, Robert. (2001). *Guide to the Software Engineering Body of Knowledge - Trial Version (Version 0,9)*. 10.13140\\/RG.2.2.12202.44489.\\n8.  Gupta, A., Xavier, S., & Sharma, S. (n.d.). Software Maintenance: Challenges and Issues. https:\\/\\/www.ijcse.net\\/docs\\/IJCSE15-04-01-037.pdf\"}', 'Software Maintenance: Processes and Challenges', NULL, '2025-11-15 09:04:22');

