(90, 10, 'Summarization\'s Impact on Sentiment Preservation', 'This study aims to systematically evaluate how text summarization, specifically at varying compression ratios and using both extractive and abstractive methods, affects sentiment preservation. By employing sentiment-labelled datasets and analyzing generated summaries with a pretrained classifier, the research will measure accuracy loss, polarity flip rates, and confidence changes. The goal is to identify which summarization techniques and compression levels best maintain sentiment integrity, offering practical guidance for sentiment-sensitive applications and contributing to the development of more reliable NLP pipelines.', '2025-11-09 15:40:32'),
(95, 37, 'Software Maintenance: Evolution, Sustainment, and DevOps', 'The BMSE3014 Software Maintenance course focuses on the evolution and sustainment of software systems, crucial for adapting to changing user needs and environments. Software maintenance itself involves modifying existing software to correct faults, improve performance, or adapt to new conditions, with a goal of extending its useful life. While the course structure includes coursework and an exam, it also delves into concepts like DevOps, a methodology emphasizing collaboration and automation between development and operations teams, which aims to improve the efficiency and appeal of software maintenance by fostering a \"you build it, you own it\" philosophy and integrating maintenance into the overall DevOps lifecycle.', '2025-11-14 14:21:36'),
(96, 41, 'Software Maintenance Essentials', 'Software maintenance encompasses a variety of activities aimed at ensuring a software system functions correctly, remains relevant, and is secure throughout its operational life. This process involves proactive and reactive measures to fix issues, adapt to environmental changes, enhance functionality, and prevent future problems. Maintenance operates under constraints of existing systems, often with shorter timeframes than initial development, and faces challenges in selecting appropriate test data. Maintenance activities are classified based on their intention (corrective, adaptive, perfective, preventive) and the nature of the changes (corrections and enhancements), with evidence-based classifications also considering observable modifications. Standardized processes like the IEEE Maintenance Process and ISO/IEC 14764 outline structured approaches, while various maintenance models, including reuse-oriented ones, guide how these activities are performed, addressing significant challenges like cost, impact analysis, and program comprehension.', '2025-11-15 09:04:48'),
(97, 41, 'Software Maintenance Overview', 'Software maintenance encompasses a range of activities aimed at keeping software operational and evolving. Key characteristics include monitoring daily operations, controlling changes, improving current functions, fixing security vulnerabilities, and preventing performance degradation. Maintenance is unique due to its operational context, requiring compatibility with existing systems, and often operates within shorter timeframes compared to initial development, with challenges in selecting appropriate test data.\n\nClassifications of software maintenance are broadly categorized by intention, activity, and evidence. Intention-based classification, as defined by ISO/IEC 14764, includes corrective (fixing problems), adaptive (adapting to environmental changes), perfective (improving user experience and efficiency), and preventive (addressing flaws before they manifest). Activity-based classification further divides these into corrections and enhancements, differentiating between proactive and reactive approaches.\n\nEvidence-based classification focuses on objective measurements of software changes, considering factors like hardware, operating systems, and organizational processes. This approach clusters activities based on modifications to the entire software, documentation, code properties, or user experience. Support interfaces, such as training and consultative services, are also crucial, as are documentation activities like reformative (improving readability) and updative (replacing outdated information) efforts.\n\nSoftware properties and business rules also inform maintenance classifications. Groomative activities improve system maintainability and performance, while reductive actions aim to decrease data input or output. Corrective business rule maintenance fixes detected flaws, and enhancive activities add or change rules to expand functionality. These classifications are often aided by decision trees to guide the maintenance process.\n\nDespite its importance, software maintenance presents significant challenges. It constitutes a substantial portion of overall software costs, with enhancements being a major driver. Impact analysis is crucial but complex, and corrective and adaptive changes can be difficult due to code complexity and evolving technologies. Program comprehension remains a vital skill for maintenance engineers, who often dedicate considerable time to understanding existing codebases. Standardized processes like the IEEE and ISO/IEC maintenance models provide structured frameworks for managing these activities.', '2025-11-15 09:38:27');

